`crates/ctx-context/src/` is the whole `ctx-context` binary crate: a read-only context server that, given a repo path, computes the ordered chain of rollup/intent/leaf `.ctx` files above it and either prints it (CLI mode) or injects the unseen portion of it as `additionalContext` into a Claude Code tool-use hook. Depending on this crate means depending on its two entry points, `cli::dispatch` and `hook::run`, both generic over the `Env` trait so all filesystem/env-var access is fake-able in tests; nothing outside `main.rs` touches `std::fs`/`std::env` directly.

The crate is organized as a straight pipeline shared by both modes: `repo_path` validates untrusted path strings into `RepoPath` (the sole gate for path-escape safety), `chain` turns a validated path into an ordered list of `ChainNode`s (rollup/intent/leaf, top-down), `serve` resolves those nodes to actual file content or a soft `(absent: …)` marker and renders the `=== id [kind] ===` text format, and `session` deduplicates served node ids per Claude session so repeated hook/CLI calls don't re-show the same node. `cli.rs` and `hook.rs` are the two callers of this pipeline — `cli::dispatch` for manual/path invocations, `hook::run` for the harness's `PostToolUse` event — and both go through `serve::fresh_chain_for` when a session id is available, which is what makes CLI and hook invocations share one dedup ledger via the `CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID` env var (`session::ENV_SESSION_ID`). Changing that env var name, `session::state_path`'s sanitization, or the served-node id format breaks that cross-mode sharing.

Error handling is asymmetric by design: `chain`/`repo_path`/`serve` treat missing scaffolding files as a normal, non-error state (absent marker), while `session::load` and `hook::run` are fail-open even on corrupt state or malformed input — the crate's only hard errors are unreadable-but-present files, invalid paths, or a broken output writer. `error.rs` centralizes every failure mode as a `CtxError` variant (no `anyhow`/`Box<dyn Error>`), so a new failure path requires a new variant there rather than a wrapped error elsewhere. `env.rs` is the sole abstraction boundary for I/O, used by `serve`, `session`, and `hook`; `lib.rs`/`main.rs` just wire the module tree and keep all process/argv/stdin I/O in the binary shell, per the crate's print-stdout lint restriction (`main.rs`/`cli.rs` route everything through injected writers, never `println!`).